Canonical correspondence analysis for winter controls on phytoplankton distribution

1 Introduction

This document presents a multivariate analysis of the relationships between trace metals and phytoplankton community composition. It provides a brief overview of the stastical methods and interpretation. This is followed by the code and outputs.

2 Method overview

The factors influencing the phytoplankton community structure were investigated using a canonical correspondence analysis (CCA). The analysis was conducted in R using the cca function from the Vegan package. The biotic variables were represented by the CHEMTAX-derived taxonomical groups biomass (g/L of Chl a). The CCA was repeated for multiple sets of environmental parameters:

  • temperature, salinity, macronutrients, trace metals (dissolved and particulate) for all stations that include trace metals.
  • Macronutrients for all stations for all stations excluding station I008
  • Dissolved trace metals for all stations excluding station I008
  • Particulate trace metals for all stations excluding station I008

Permutation tests were run based on 999 permutations to evaluate the significance of the CCA axes and the significance of the environmental variables.

Figure 3.1: Density plots of CHEMTAX derived taxonomical groups biomass (g/L of Chl a)

From the density plots above, the phytoplankton biomass for the various taxonomic groups appear to be unimodal.

Figure 3.2: Density distribution plots of environmental variables

The density plots above show that the nutrient distributions are mostly unimodal.

Variance inflation factors were calculated using the vif.cca function. Variance inflation is an indicator of redundancy/colinearity of variables. Variance inflation factors greater than 10 generally indicate that the colinearity of the variables is likely to hinder interpretation of the CCA. The user guide states:

Variance inflation is a diagnostic tool to identify useless constraints. A common rule is that values over 10 indicate redundant constraints. If later constraints are complete linear combinations of conditions or previous constraints, they will be completely removed from the estimation, and no biplot scores or centroids are calculated for these aliased constraint.

Variance inflation factors were calculated using the vif.cca function. Variance inflation is an indicator of redundancy/colinearity of variables. Variance inflation factors greater than 10 generally indicate that the colinearity of the variables is likely to hinder interpretation of the CCA. The user guide states:

Variance inflation is a diagnostic tool to identify useless constraints. A common rule is that values over 10 indicate redundant constraints. If later constraints are complete linear combinations of conditions or previous constraints, they will be completely removed from the estimation, and no biplot scores or centroids are calculated for these aliased constraint.
